                    <dhq:affiliation>KU Leuven and International Institute of Social History, Amsterdam</dhq:affiliation>
                    <email>hilde.deweerdt@kuleuven.be</email>
                    <dhq:bio>
                        <p>Hilde De Weerdt is Professor of Chinese and Early Modern Global History at KU Leuven and Senior Researcher at the International Institute of 
                            Social History, Amsterdam. Professor De Weerdt is broadly interested in social, political, and intellectual history, both within an East Asian context, and within a comparative or global historical framework. 
                            She has published six books on Chinese political culture, focusing on the workings of late imperial Chinese bureaucratic infrastructures and political communication. 
                            Professor De Weerdt maintains an active interest in designing and developing digital research methods for East Asian and other languages. With Brent Ho et al. she co-designed the text annotation 
                            and reading services ENTMARKUS and COMARKUS, with Rainer Simon et al. the image annotation service IMMARKUS, with Tu Hsieh-Chang and Lin Nung-Yao et al. the cross-media search and information retrieval 
                            system X-MARKUS and the spatial analysis platform MUNDa, and with Mees Gelein two text comparison modules COMPARATIVUS and PARALLELLS.  
                            She is currently working on a large project sponsored by the European Research Council and the Dutch Research Council on the longue-dur√©e 
                            social and regional history of material infrastructures.</p>
                    </dhq:bio>
                </dhq:authorInfo>
                    
                <dhq:authorInfo>
                    <dhq:author_name>Rainer <dhq:family>Simon</dhq:family></dhq:author_name>
                    <idno type="ORCID">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4116-9684</idno>
                    <dhq:affiliation>Independent research software engineer</dhq:affiliation>
                    <email>rainer@rainersimon.io</email>
                    <dhq:bio>
                        <p>Rainer Simon is an independent research software engineer. He has been working in the field of information management, knowledge engineering, and user 
                            interface design for more than 15 years, with a focus on Digital Humanities and the Digital Library field. He has been collaborating with major GLAM 
                            (Galleries, Libraries, Archives, Museums) and academic partners worldwide, and published extensively on technological issues of digital representation, 
                            data modelling and systems design in this domain. Dr. Simon is the former lead developer of the award-winning Recogito annotation platform, and the maintainer of 
                            several open-source technologies for text- and image-annotation. Together with Professor De Weerdt he co-designed the image annotation service IMMARKUS.</p>
                    </dhq:bio>
                </dhq:authorInfo>
                    
                    <dhq:authorInfo>
                    <dhq:author_name>Sunkyu <dhq:family>Lee</dhq:family></dhq:author_name>
                    <idno type="ORCID">https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0519-138X</idno>
                    <dhq:affiliation>KU Leuven </dhq:affiliation>
                    <email>sunkyu.lee@kuleuven.be</email>
                    <dhq:bio>
                        <p>Sunkyu Lee is a postdoctoral researcher at KU Leuven on the project Regionalizing Infrastructures in Chinese History. 
                            She is a social and cultural historian of early modern China and East Asia, with a particular focus on cartography and frontier histories. Her current project, Steppe, Forest, and River: 
                            Wall Histories in East Asia between the Fifteenth and Seventeenth Centuries, investigates how wall-building emerged as a common strategy 
                            across geographically and culturally diverse frontiers in early modern East Asia. Using digital methodologies, the project traces cross-regional patterns of 
                            boundary-making and analyzes how local ecologies, material practices, and technological transfer shaped frontier infrastructures in concert. 
                            She also contributed to the development of the IMMARKUS platform.</p>
                    </dhq:bio>
